So come back to the ground. The sculpture in Holmdel is still there. The mirrored Bell Works building, once Bell Labs' palace on a hill, is still standing — reborn in twenty-thirteen as Bell Works, a two-million-square-foot 'metroburb' filled with startups, restaurants, and a quarter-mile atrium open to the public. And twenty miles south of it, on the same Fort Monmouth soil where the Signal Corps laboratories once bought the first transistors, Netflix is now pouring concrete. A one-billion-dollar, twelve-soundstage East Coast production hub. Phase one opens in twenty-twenty-seven. The ground that made the thing that makes the shows is now making the studio where the shows get made. That is not coincidence. That is how this place works. Every layer of the computer age was built inside a twenty-mile strip of New Jersey — and we are going to walk through all of them, one layer at a time.
